    <!-- SOUR SCIENCE -->
    <h2>What Makes a Great Sour Gummy Worm</h2>

    <p>Sour gummy worms are defined by their coating — a dusting of citric acid and/or malic acid that creates the initial mouth-puckering tang before the sweet gummy interior takes over. The best sour worms balance three elements: sourness intensity, sweetness payoff, and chew texture. Here is what separates premium sour worms from the rest.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Sour Coating</h4>
        <p>Citric acid (from citrus) and malic acid (from apples) are both plant-derived — the sour coating itself is always vegan. The difference between brands is coating density: more acid per surface area means more initial punch. SmartSweets and Project 7 have the heaviest coatings.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="sparkle" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Two-Tone Flavor</h4>
        <p>Classic gummy worms have two colors with two distinct flavors — one per half. The best vegan worms replicate this dual-flavor design, giving each worm a flavor combination (e.g., strawberry-lemon, grape-orange) rather than a single uniform taste.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="target" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Chew Length</h4>
        <p>The elongated worm shape creates more surface area and chew time than compact gummy bears. Pectin-based worms can be softer than gelatin, but the best formulations (SmartSweets, Lovely Candy Co) achieve satisfying chew resistance that makes each worm last.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Natural vs Artificial Sour</h4>
        <p>All vegan worms on this list use natural citric and malic acid. Conventional brands like Trolli use the same acids but add artificial colors (Red 40, Blue 1) and artificial flavors. The sourness level is comparable — the difference is what else is in the worm.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

